      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prompt Caching for Static Slots"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "System prompts and large reference documents are re-sent on every API call. Prompt caching writes these static blocks to a server-side cache on the first call, then reads from cache on subsequent calls at 0.1\u00d7 the base input price. For agents with large system prompts or persisted documents, caching can cut input costs by 80\u201390%. Mark blocks with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "cache_control: {type: 'ephemeral'}",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " \u2014 the cache lives for 5 minutes and resets on any modification."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Prompt caching: avoid re-processing static content on every turn\n# Saves cost and speeds up inference for large system prompts / documents\nimport anthropic\n\nclient = anthropic.Anthropic()\n\n# Mark a large static block for caching with cache_control\n# The block must be >= 1024 tokens (Claude 3 family) to be cached\ndef build_cached_request(\n    system: str,\n    static_document: str,   # large reference doc, loaded once\n    messages: list[dict],\n) -> dict:\n    return {\n        'model': 'claude-sonnet-5',\n        'max_tokens': 4096,\n        'system': [\n            # Part 1: static instructions \u2014 will be cached after first call\n            {\n                'type': 'text',\n                'text': system,\n                'cache_control': {'type': 'ephemeral'},\n            },\n            # Part 2: large reference document \u2014 cached separately\n            {\n                'type': 'text',\n                'text': static_document,\n                'cache_control': {'type': 'ephemeral'},\n            },\n        ],\n        'messages': messages,\n    }\n\n# Caching economics (as of 2025):\n# Cache write:  1.25x base input price (one-time)\n# Cache read:   0.10x base input price (every subsequent call)\n#\n# For a 50k-token system prompt called 100x:\n# Without cache: 100 * 50k * base_price\n# With cache:    1 * 50k * 1.25 * base_price + 99 * 50k * 0.10 * base_price\n#                = 11.15x base_price  (vs 100x) \u2014 ~89% cost reduction\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Adaptive Budgeting by Turn Type"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A single fixed allocation wastes budget. A retrieval turn needs 40\u201350% of the window for documents; a tool-heavy turn needs 50% for tool results; a conversational turn can put most of the budget into history. An adaptive budget selects a pre-defined allocation profile based on the detected turn type, shifting tokens to where they are actually needed."
